+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.wbench "Workbench"
@version 0.282
@toc Workbench

    - Workbench -

            This menu item provides access to menu items used for
        the operation of the Workbench as opposed to the files it
        manipulates or the directory structure (windows).

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.backdrop "Backdrop"
@version 0.282
@toc Workbench

    - Backdrop -

            The Workbench may appear as the full screen, with disk
        icons appearing on the draggable screen. Or, it may function
        in a movable window much like a directory or drawer window.
        The user may set a background pattern, a backdrop picture, or
        a screen picture. The screen picture or pattern is only visible
        when the Workbench is not a backdrop.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.execute "Execute Command"
@version 0.282
@toc Workbench

    - Execute Command -

            As opposed to opening a Shell, the user may use this menu
        item to open a small input requester. This is similar to typing
        one command at the Shell prompt. Commands may be passed, and an
        output window will be opened if necessary.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.re_all "Redraw All"
@version 0.232
@toc Workbench

    - Redraw All -

            In the event that a program has drawn an image over the
        Workbench, causing some screen data to be lost, this will
        redraw the windows and backdrops to their original state.
        This is useful when Workbench Hacks are used, which are
        designed to play harmless tricks with the Workbench imagery.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.up_all "Update All"
@version 0.232
@toc Workbench

    - Update All -

            In some occassions, a program or shell may alter the
        contents of a directory without notifying the Workbench.
        Therefor, an icon may appear on the Workbench even though it
        has been deleted or duplicated. This menu item will redraw
        and update the contents of each window, similar to closing and
        reopening each window.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.last "Last Message"
@version 0.282
@toc Workbench

    - Last Message -

            This will display the last error message displayed in
        the title bar of the Workbench screen.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.about "About"
@version 0.282
@toc Workbench

    - About -

            To display the current versions of the Workbench, select
        this menu item to open a small display window. Both the
        Kickstart and the Workbench versions will be displayed.

                            KS1.3       v34.x
                            KS2.04      v37.175
                            KS3.0       v40.x

                            WB1.3       v34.x
                            WB2.04      v37.x
                            WB2.1       v38.28
                            WB3.0       v40.x

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.quit "Quit"
@version 0.282
@toc Workbench

    - Quit -

            This menu option is used to exit the Workbench. In the event
        that the Workbench has launched some programs, it will not be
        able to exit until those programs are closed also. After quitting
        the Workbench, you may restart it using the @{" LoadWB " link AORM.OS.AmigaDOS/loadwb} command.

            WARNING: If you quit the Workbench and do not have access to
        a shell or other program, you may lose the ability to lauch new
        programs. A reboot will then be required.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.window "Window"
@version 2.032
@toc Workbench

    - Window -

            All operations on the currently selected window are listed
        in this submenu. The target window must be selected. Otherwise,
        the options will appear ghosted.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.new "New Drawer"
@version 2.032
@toc Workbench

    - New Drawer -

            This creates a new drawer in the selected window, and allows
        the user to specify a name for the new drawer by opening a
        requester.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.parent "Open Parent"
@version 2.032
@toc Workbench

    - Open Parent -

            This will open the parent drawer, if one is available.
        The parent drawer contains the current drawer.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.close "Close"
@version 2.032
@toc Workbench

    - Close -

            This will close the current drawer or window.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.update "Update"
@version 2.032
@toc Workbench

    - Update -

            In some occassions, a program or shell may alter the
        contents of a directory without notifying the Workbench.
        Therefor, an icon may appear on the Workbench even though it
        has been deleted or duplicated. This menu item will redraw
        and update the contents of the selected  window, similar to
        closing and reopening that window.


@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.select "Select Contents"
@version 2.032
@toc Workbench

    - Select Contents -

            This will select all of the icon images in the current
        window, similar to using the SHIFT key to select every window.
        A group of windows may also be selected by creating a rubber
        banding drag box around them.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.cleanup "Cleanup"
@version 2.032
@toc Workbench

    - Cleanup -

            This will organize the icons in the current window so
        that they appear in one group, aligned, and to fit the
        size of the window, if possible. The new locations of the
        files are not recorded to disk unless the @{" Snapshot " link wb.snapshot} option
        is used.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.snapshot "Snapshot"
@version 2.086
@toc Workbench

    - Snapshot -

            This option will store the contents of all of the icons in
        their current positions. This will also store the size and the
        positions of the Workbench windows. If the Window submenu item
        isselected, only the current window will be snapshotted. If the
        All submenu item is selected, every window and icon, including
        those for volumes, will be saved. If your volumes are write
        protected, a requester will open to remind you.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.show "Show"
@version 2.086
@toc Workbench

    - Show -

            This option will allow you to see files and drawers that do
        not have .info files or icons. Default icons will be used to
        represent them. These default icons cannot be modified since no
        .info file exists. To create a .info file, use either IconEdit,
        a public domain program, or make a duplicate of another icon.
        To view just files with icons, select the Only Icons submenu
        item. Use the All Files submenu item in order to see every file.
        Some files, such as .info files themselves, may not be listed,
        however their associated files will be.


            Here are some sample directory listings of a fictitious
        SYS: volume.

            Only Icons          All Files           Shell
            --------------      --------------      --------------
            DataTypes           DataTypes           .info
            DOSDrivers          DOSDrivers          DataTypes
            Prefs               L                   DataTypes.info
            System              LIBS                DOSDrivers
            Utilities           S                   DOSDrivers.info
            WBStartup           System              L
                                T                   LIBS
                                Utilities           S
                                WBStartup           System
                                                    System.info
                                                    T
                                                    Utilities
                                                    Utilities.info
                                                    WBStartup
                                                    WBStartup.info

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.view_by "View By"
@version 2.086
@toc Workbench

    - View By -

            This allows you to define how you wish the files to be
        represented in a Workbench window. You may view files by their
        corresponding icons, by an alphabetical listing of text, by
        a dated listing of text (newest first), or by their file sizes,
        with the smallest first. If viewed by icon, only the icon and
        the filename will be displayed. If by name, date, or size, only
        the filename, size, protection bits, date, and time will be
        displayed, with no icon images.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.icons "Icons"
@version 2.080
@toc Workbench

    - Icons -

            The Icons menu allows you to perform operations on icons,
        such as duplicating, renaming, or deleting. This menu also
        allows you to format disks.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.open "Open"
@version 2.086
@toc Workbench

    - Open -

            This will open a file if its icon is selected. If it is a
        drawer, the drawer will be opened. If it is an executable file
        or script, it will be executed. If it is a projected, it will
        load its application and the project. If multiple drawers are
        selected, they will all be opened.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.copy "Copy"
@version 2.086
@toc Workbench

    - Copy -

            This will make a copy of a file or drawer, which will be
        renamed. The new name will be the original name preceeded by
        Copy_of.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.rename "Rename"
@version 2.086
@toc Workbench

    - Rename -

            This allows you to rename a file, drawer, or volume. This
        cannot be done on files that have been left out using the Leave
        Out menu item.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.info "Information"
@version 2.086
@toc Workbench

    - Information -

            This will open a Workbench window with information regarding
        the current file. It allows you to change the stack size, the
        protection bits, tool types, default tool, and the comment.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.snap "Snapshot"
@version 2.086
@toc Workbench

    - Snapshot -

            This will store the location of the selected icon on the
        current volume, in the current Workbench window. This allows
        the icon to remain in a new position after rebooting. This
        will write the new location of the icon to the volume it is on.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.unsnap "Unsnapshot"
@version 2.086
@toc Workbench

    - Unsnapshot -

            This will remove the snapshot placed onto an icon. This is
        used when the files are to be alphabetized in a Workbench window
        that is displaying icon images. It can also be used to alert the
        Workbench to place it on the backdrop or window in the order that
        it is loaded by the Workbench.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.leave "Leave Out"
@version 2.086
@toc Workbench

    - Leave Out -

            This will allow a drawer or file to be left on the Workbench
        backdrop even after rebooting the computer. If a file is left out,
        there may be limitations on how it can be renamed. When this
        option is selected, the Workbench will store the information on
        the volume it came from, in the root directory, in a file called
        ".backdrop".

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.put_away "Put Away"
@version 2.086
@toc Workbench

    - Put Away -

            This will return any left out files to their original
        Workbench window location.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.delete "Delete"
@version 2.032
@toc Workbench

    - Delete -

            This allows a faster way of deleting files or drawers
        without using the Trashcan. The disadvantage is that once
        a file or drawer is deleted, it cannot be restored using
        normal means, and it may not be recoverable once the space
        is allocated to another file.
            A requester will open to verify that you wish to perform
        the file deletion. All selected files and drawers will be
        deleted. Deleting a drawer will also delete the entire
        contents of the drawer.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.format "Format Disk"
@version 2.032
@toc Workbench

    - Format Disk -

            A disk may be formatted with this menu, including the 880k
        floppies, 1.76 megabyte floppies, hard drives, RAD:, and other
        devices. They may be formatted using various file systems,
        such as OFS, FFS, and DCFS.


            Current Information     Displays device name, volume name,
                                    size, and percentage used

            New Volume Name         Allows the user to enter a new
                                    name for the disk; defaults to
                                    Empty

            Put Trashcan            Specifies whether a Trashcan should
                                    be created on the disk

            Fast File System        Specifies the use of the Fast File
                                    System as opposed to the Old File
                                    System

            International Mode      Specifies International Mode

            Directory Cache         Specifies Directory Caching, which
                                    improves directory reads greatly
                                    yet decreases write speeds.

            Format                  Executes routine to reformat the
                                    disk, removing all existing data

            Quick Format            Executes the Quick Format routine,
                                    which merely preps the disk by
                                    erasing the directories. May not be
                                    used on a disk that has never been
                                    formatted before

            Cancel                  Cancels the operation


        NOTE: The majority of Amiga users may not be able to read
              Fast File System, International Mode, or Directory
              Cached disks. For distribution, it is suggested that
              the defaults be used, although 2.x users may use Fast
              File System, and 3.x users may use International Mode
              or Directory Caching.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.empty "Empty Trash"
@version 2.032
@toc Workbench

    - Empty Trash -

            Any file stored in the Trashcan is not actually deleted
        until this menu item is selected. Files placed in the Trashcan
        are actually moved into a special directory on the current
        partition. Each partition must have its own Trashcan.
            Rebooting, turning the power off, and launching programs
        does not delete any of the files in the Trashcan.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.tools "Tools"
@version 2.032
@toc Workbench

    - Tools -

            This menu is customizable, such that each item must be
        programmed by the user into the menu list. It may contain
        any executable file or command, including scripts and
        ARexx scripts. Programs such as ToolsX and ToolManager will
        program this, among many others.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


@node wb.resetwb "ResetWB"
@version 2.032
@toc Workbench

    - ResetWB -

            This will attempt to reset the Workbench, all of its windows,
        and any icon images.

@endnode
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------+


